If your types are not related each other from a use case point of view you should use different types to avoid coupling between unrelated entities. It will later save you the effort if they diverge independently.

If they are related you can leverage extension. Take out the common attributes into a base type and extend the other types from this base type.

    
    &lt;xsd:complexType name=&quot;MyBaseComplexType&quot;&gt;
      &lt;xsd:sequence&gt;
        &lt;!-- Common Elements --&gt;
        &lt;xsd:element name=&quot;FirstName&quot; type=&quot;xsd:string&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;xsd:element name=&quot;LastName&quot; type=&quot;xsd:string&quot;/&gt;

      &lt;/xsd:sequence&gt;
    &lt;/xsd:complexType&gt;


    &lt;xsd:complexType name=&quot;CustomComplexType&quot;&gt;
      &lt;xsd:complexContent&gt;
        &lt;xsd:extension base=&quot;MyComplexType&quot;&gt;
          &lt;xsd:sequence&gt;
            &lt;xsd:element name=&quot;Age&quot; type=&quot;xsd:string&quot;/&gt;
          &lt;/xsd:sequence&gt;
        &lt;/xsd:extension&gt;
      &lt;/xsd:complexContent&gt;
    &lt;/xsd:complexType&gt;

    &lt;xsd:complexType name=&quot;OtherCustomComplexType&quot;&gt;
        &lt;xsd:complexContent&gt;
            &lt;xsd:extension base=&quot;MyComplexType&quot;&gt;
              &lt;xsd:sequence&gt;
                &lt;xsd:element name=&quot;SomeOtherAttribute&quot; type=&quot;xsd:string&quot;/&gt;
              &lt;/xsd:sequence&gt;
            &lt;/xsd:extension&gt;
        &lt;/xsd:complexContent&gt;
    &lt;/xsd:complexType&gt;


The `CustomComplexType` and `OtherCustomComplexType` will now contain `FirstName` and `LastName`

